**Audience blind spots:**
- Readers who don't identify as "goth" but are drawn to witchy aesthetic — they're not being spoken to
- The cottagecore/dark academia crossover audience who want soft, earthy witchy rather than dark dramatic
- Short nail wearers who feel excluded from witchy content that defaults to stiletto/coffin length

### Our Strategic Approach

**Differentiation:** Frame witchy nails as an aesthetic spectrum with named sub-aesthetics rather than a single look — giving readers a way to self-identify and save the right ideas. Lead with year-round wearability, not Halloween. Write for the woman who feels a witchy mood, not the costume seeker.

**Structure plan:** Organise by aesthetic type (celestial, forest, dark gothic, pastel/soft, minimalist) rather than by symbol or colour. Layer in shape and finish guidance as tools for each aesthetic. Include the crossover note for whimsigoth and cottagecore readers.

**Tone direction:** Aspirational and empowering — position the witchy aesthetic as intentional, beautiful self-expression, not costume play.

